2026-03-20 | Minimum Absolute Difference in KxK Submatrix

	Question
For every k×k submatrix, compute:
		min |a - b| for all distinct pairs

	Approach
Brute force per window:
		collect elements → sort → check adjacent differences  

Optimized approach:
1.	Slide k×k window over grid  
2.	For each window:
		- insert elements into multiset (sorted order)
		- iterate once to find min adjacent difference  
3.	Store result  

Optimization:
Instead of recomputing from scratch:
		we can still keep it simple since k ≤ small (usually constraints)

	Time Complexity
	O((m−k+1)(n−k+1) × k² log(k²))

	Space Complexity
	O(k²)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> minDifference(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {

        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();

        vector<vector<int>> ans(m - k + 1, vector<int>(n - k + 1, 0));

        for (int i = 0; i <= m - k; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j <= n - k; j++) {

                vector<int> vals;

                // collect k x k elements
                for (int x = i; x < i + k; x++) {
                    for (int y = j; y < j + k; y++) {
                        vals.push_back(grid[x][y]);
                    }
                }

                sort(vals.begin(), vals.end());

                int minDiff = INT_MAX;

                for (int t = 1; t < vals.size(); t++) {
                    minDiff = min(minDiff, abs(vals[t] - vals[t - 1]));
                }

                ans[i][j] = (minDiff == INT_MAX ? 0 : minDiff);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

	Key Insight
The minimum absolute difference always comes from **adjacent elements after sorting**.  

So instead of checking all pairs (O(k⁴)),
we reduce it to O(k² log k²) per window.

	If constraints are very large:
→ can further optimize using frequency arrays (if values bounded)  
→ or sliding window with ordered set reuse.
